			<title>New 10 inch tablet decision...</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76827-New-10-inch-tablet-decision&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 23 May 2014 07:12:52 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[So I've managed to lose my Nexus 7 and was looking at getting another tablet to replace it.  Now, in all honestly my Nexus 7 experience wasn't that great.  I found it slow to turn on, slow to charge, battery hungry in standby and frequently locked up.  Having said that mine was one of the first...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>So I've managed to lose my Nexus 7 and was looking at getting another tablet to replace it.  Now, in all honestly my Nexus 7 experience wasn't that great.  I found it slow to turn on, slow to charge, battery hungry in standby and frequently locked up.  Having said that mine was one of the first production ones so I think I got a bit of a lemon as everyone else I know with one had much better experiences.<br />
Regardless, the longer I had it, the slower it went, randomly froze and increasingly just crashed apps.  So much so that I really feel no loss at it disappearing.<br />
<br />
This time around I'm looking at a 10 inch tablet though my budget tops out at about $500<br />
<br />
I'd been looking at the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Samsung-Galaxy-Note-Edition-Black/dp/B00F3SOJ7O/ref=sr_1_11?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1400823668&amp;sr=8-11&amp;keywords=samsung+galaxy+note" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Samsung Galaxy Note 10.1 (2014)</a> - price here is $520 (in white which isn't my first choice)<br />
This tablet seems decent, speedy, bright and the stylus seems useful.  Added to that it has a 4G connection so I could conceivably use it outside of my home or office wifi.<br />
<br />
But today I had a play with the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Transformer-T100TA-C1-GR-Detachable-Touchscreen-Laptop/dp/B00FFJ0HUE/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1400822876&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=asus+t100" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Asus Transformerbook T100</a> and been quite impressed - best price here is $450.  The keyboard dock bit is pretty appealing and thanks to my gf's laptop I'm getting used to windows 8 these days.<br />
<br />
Has anyone used either of these and can give me some more impressions?<br />
<br />
<u>Activities I'd use them for</u><br />
Either would give me access to reading comics &amp; magazines - potentially the Samsung slightly better on the magazine side.  Ebooks I'm not concerned with - my kindle has that covered.  Both would let me stream movies from my Plex server.  Windows 8 would have working flash in browsers which would be nice.<br />
Both of them I could use HDMI out to send presentations to a projector.  The Asus has a slight advantage coming with Office Home &amp; Student 2013 bundled so I could pull up work docs without any formatting/formulas potentially changing.  Additionally it could run Articulate Storyline (for shorter e-learning modules anyway).<br />
Gaming - Actually one area where I'd sort of prefer an ipad (but thats at least $150 more) as I would play things like Ticket to Ride vs my gf on her ipad mini.  Android is ok for games but I never played anything overly memorable on the Nexus 7.  For mobile gaming I'd use my 3DS instead so I'm just looking for couch or in bed gaming.  The ASUS game ability is very attractive, I've seen youtube videos of it running Portal 2 and there's probably 100+ games in my steam library with less system requirements than Portal 2.  And this new Steam streaming thing might work too with the ASUS.<br />
Space - both accept micro SD cards and while the ASUS is 64gb, you only get 34 after windows install so thats essentially identical.<br />
Photos - I think I could actually get some decent photo sorting going with the Asus, I never found an easy way to do that with android. But the Asus screen resolution could be a limiting factor for doing any image editing.<br />
<br />
If I lived in the US the Asus can be had for about $350 which I'd grab with no hesitation.  But the cost jump here puts it in direct competition with the Samsung (actually at most stores the prices are identical at $599). I think the Asus is the better choice, but I can't help but think this is kinda like Zune vs Ipod or Nokia N95 vs Iphone.  Technically better, but regretting it if you do.  Or maybe they're both Zunes and I should save another 4 months for a higher capacity ipad.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
